############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context("LimitedFraction"); $m = Fraction(-5,6);
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML A line passes through the points [`(-18,14)`] and [`(18,-16)\text{.}`] Find this line's slope.
[_]{$m}{10}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION To find a line's slope, we can use the slope formula:
[```\text{slope}=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}```]
First, we mark which number corresponds to which variable in the formula:
[```(\overset{x_1}{-18},\overset{y_1}{14})\qquad(\overset{x_2}{18},\overset{y_2}{-16})```]
Now we substitute these numbers into the corresponding variables in the slope formula:
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} \text{slope} \amp =\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\\ \amp =\frac{-16-14}{18-(-18)}\\ \amp =\frac{-30}{36}\\ \amp =\frac{-5}{6} \end{aligned} ```]
So the line's slope is [`-\frac56\text{.}`]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
